[2m2026-05-20T13:22:08.539167Z[0m [32m INFO[0m [2mphantom_loop::dispatcher::driver[0m[2m:[0m agent tool use [3magent_id[0m[2m=[0m50000 [3mround[0m[2m=[0m30 [3mtool[0m[2m=[0mRunCommand [3margs[0m[2m=[0m{"command":"cat > /tmp/comment.md <<'EOF'\nImplementer triage analysis — this issue appears to be misscoped and blocked. Posting findings before pausing.\n\n## `router.peer_keys` does not exist\n\nA workspace-wide search for `peer_keys` (and `peer_key`, `PeerKey`, `trusted_keys`, `known_keys`) finds zero hits in any `.rs` file:\n\n```\n$ grep -rln \"peer_keys\" crates/ docs/\n(no results)\n```\n\nPR #519 (the carve-out source) did not introduce such a field either — its diff touches `signing.rs`, `agent_route.rs`, and consolidates `CapabilityClass`, but never adds a peer-key registry to `Router`. The current `phantom-relay::router::Router` fields are: `sessions`, `rate_buckets`, `grants`, `rate_limit`, `max_peers`, `deny_unsigned`. No key store.\n\n## The current handshake design intentionally has no persistent registry\n\nPer `phantom-relay::server::handle_connection` and the issue-#526 doc-comment at the top of `server.rs`:\n\n> The relay rejects trust-on-first-use. On every new connection:\n> 1. Server sends a `Challenge` frame containing 32 bytes of fresh entropy.\n> 2. Client replies with `IdentityProof { peer_id, public_key, signature }`.\n> 3. Server verifies the signature with the supplied public key.\n\nThe peer's public key is **presented fresh on every handshake** and verified via proof-of-possession against a server-issued challenge. The relay does not need to remember the key between connections — it re-verifies PoP on each connect. \"Peers must re-register on restart\" is the *designed* behaviour, not a bug, because re-registration = re-proving possession of the private key.\n\nIf we wanted a pinned/persistent registry (peer_id → expected_public_key, reject if a connecting peer presents a different key), that would be a **new feature** (TOFU-pinning with persistence), not a \"make existing in-memory field persistent\" refactor as the issue describes. That's a meaningful design decision that should be re-scoped in its own issue with clear threat model justification.\n\n## Blocked on #401 regardless\n\nEven if we wanted to implement a persistent key registry today, the acceptance criteria say \"Postgres preferred per #401\" and #401 (Phase 3 Postgres schema) is still **open and entirely unimplemented**:\n\n- No `sqlx` dependency in `phantom-hub/Cargo.toml`\n- No `crates/phantom-hub/migrations/` directory\n- No `db.rs`\n- No `DATABASE_URL` wiring\n- No Railway Postgres addon\n\nLanding #527 before #401 means either (a) inventing a parallel persistence layer (sled / SQLite / JSON file) that will be ripped out when #401 lands — duplicated work the issue explicitly warns against — or (b) building all of #401's Postgres scaffolding inside #527, which is the wrong issue for that scope.\n\n## Recommendation\n\n1. Close or hold this issue until #401 lands.\n2. If/when reopened, re-scope to describe the actual feature being requested. Two distinct possibilities:\n   - **(a) Key pinning**: persist `(peer_id → public_key)` so a peer connecting under a known `peer_id` with a *different* key is rejected. This is a security feature, not a \"make in-memory durable\" refactor.\n   - **(b) Session token persistence**: persist `session_token` so reconnecting peers can resume without a full handshake. Different threat model again.\n3. Confirm the threat model so we know which (if either) of the above is desired.\n\nPausing this assignment. Happy to pick it back up once #401 has landed and the scope is clarified.\nEOF\ngh issue comment 527 -R jdmiranda/phantom --body-file /tmp/comment.md"}
